title.narrative: Piloting Elephant Energy Grass cultivation for cleaner energy and livestock feed in Wattuba, Kampala, Uganda

description.narrative: More than 90% of all energy used in Uganda comes from firewood and charcoal (44 million tons). 74% of this is used for cooking by households which adds up to at least 35 million kilos of wood being burned each day. The use of firewood and charcoal leads to deforestation, soil erosion, drought and nutrition depletion and increasing challenges to grow crops and feed livestock. Complete deforestation is forecasted for 2032 at current usage and replenishment rates. Furthermore, the use of firewood stoves leads to very dangerous situations; over 40,000 woman and children die each year from household air pollution and fires. This potential catastrophe needs to be addressed and resolved with a domestic solution.Miscanthus, also known as Elephant Grass, may offer a solution for this as is grows very fast and has the same energy value as coal. Dutch company The Green Elephant (TGE) grows Miscanthus in Uganda, turning it into animal feed, pellets and burning briquettes to combat deforestation and provide cheap, reliable and safe fuel for the poor as well as affordable and nutritional feed for smallholder farmers. In order to test and validate the production and market for elephant grass and its different applications and to prepare for future investments, Technical Assistance (DGGF-TA) provided support. The project included the set-up of a nursery and research centre for crop development, testing of diverse harvesting technologies, determining the highest yield in Ugandan conditions, preparing initial 100 ha for planting elephant grass, setting-up a briquette manufacturing plant, trials to determine the optimal ingredients for feed blocks and developing a production process for commercial volumes.The project supported 28 direct jobs, 135 indirect jobs and contributed to sustainable knowledge transfer by training 58 people, of which 30 smallholder dairy farmers in order to improve animal welfare and milk production capacity. Furthermore, the project contributed to increased awareness of the need for sustainable and safe energy sources to prevent deforestation and the advantages elephant grass offers for this. The project was successful and further investments in the plantation and factory are being prepared. These investments have the potential to supply at least 250,000 households with their daily clean fuel needs with a minimised carbon footprint and are expected to create an extra 250 new jobs within the next 5 years.
